      "source": [
        "**Data Preparation**\n",
        "\n",
        "The FISE 100 index contract data between January 2016 and March 2020 will be used for the purpose of this repository.\n",
        "\n",
        "Since the feature of interest is price volatility, whose is essentially the standard deviations of price. The volatility benchmark we established therefore,is the highest price minus the lowest price at a one-minute period and a moving average window the size of N.\n",
        "\n",
        "$Vol=\\frac{\\sum^n_i High_i - Low_i}{n}$\n",
        "\n",
        "In principle, when price significantly fluctuates, volatility should increase. To test such relationship, we randomly pick a trading day and confirm it with the respective volatility and market price. \n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "9mbHprk9TTKP",
        "colab_type": "text"
      },
      "source": [
        "In some period, volatiltiy is fairly significant. The solid line that go across the heat map illustrates the fact that volatility can be consistently high across some time period. In particular:\n",
        "\n",
        "*   0100: CFD Trading Starts\n",
        "*   0700: European Union Stock Pre-market\n",
        "*   0800: London Stock Exchange Market Open\n",
        "*   1200: Noon\n",
        "*   1430: New York Stock Exchange Market Open\n",
        "*   1630: London Stock Exchange Market Close\n",
        "\n",
        "To utilize volatilty in trading, we need it to be high and consistent. Since volatility is mostly high when market open, that is, timestamp 0800. If we used the one-hour pre-market volatility to predict the five minute volatility after market open(in which volatility is the highest within the day), then an intraday trading strategy can be carried out.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    }
